 develop an extended concept of heredity that upends ideas about how traits can and cannot be transmitted across generations. By examining the history of the gene-centered view in modern biology and reassessing fundamental tenets of evolutionary theory, Bonduriansky and Day show that nongenetic inheritance-involving epigenetic, environmental, behavioral, and cultural factors-could play an important role in evolution. The discovery of nongenetic inheritance therefore has major implications for key questions in evolutionary biology, as well as human health.Extended Heredity reappraises long-held ideas and opens the door to a new understanding of inheritance and evolution.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Sep 2021) 0aEvolution (Biology). 0aGenetics. 0aHeredity. 7aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Evolution.2bisacsh1 aDay, Troy, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060659140uhttps://doi.org/10.23943/9781400890156zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400890156423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781400890156/original  a978-3-11-060659-1  Princeton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK